                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/6836: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-23T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 23, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 23—3:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4815. The German press after having in the recent past given a good deal of space
                    to comment on the difficulty of terrain, communication and weather encountered
                    by the Italians in northern Greece, now confines its reporting of the
                    Greco-Italian war to the publication of the text of Italian war communiqués.
                    Reports of the actual extent of Italian reverses are not published in such a way
                    as to make them clearly discernible to the German public.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
